      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. and what about if i find some small holes or deep indentations in the drywall before i start mudding? like, if there are just these weird little divots or gaps in the board itself, should i just fill them with the regular joint compound or do i need something stronger?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For small divots and minor imperfections, regular joint compound will usually suffice, but for deeper holes or gouges, you should use a setting-type joint compound or a polyester filler. These thicker fillers grab and harden faster, preventing shrinkage and ensuring a solid fill underneath your finishing coat. Always apply these fillers in layers, feathering the edges out wide to blend seamlessly with the surrounding drywall surface.",
      "source": "target",
